  "messages": [
    {
      "id": "9977879b253e5389a4e30fcb8ced56e03b8fad38",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-11 02:09:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nThis looks like a good catch.  I guess in most cases, buf->lb_buf == NULL, but in a few the original mti_buf is used, and may contain random data.\n\nTo be honest, I think it would be safer to just replace the initialization of buf with LU_BUF_NULL, and remove mti_buf entirely, since I don't think it is used anywhere.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "051b49e9e529a38b0c66be989dda74021acea003",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-11 02:15:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe entire idea of mdd_buf stuff escapes me, esp. since everybody seems to need to initialize it before starting.\n\nThat's why I am hoping Mike or somebody else who knows this code deeply can chime-in.\n\nAS is it looks like by using this to pass buffers around one is also open to other parts of the code hijacking the mti buffer and filling it with something else too.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
